Measuring Apical Constriction in Drug treated embryos

David Kleinhans

2017-11-09

1 Introduction

1.1 Apical Constriction

Apical constriction is the process in which contraction of the apical side of a cell causes the cell to take on a wedged shape. Generally, this shape change is coordinated across many cells of an epithelial layer, generating forces that can bend or fold the cell sheet. - Lee, J.; Harland, R. M. (2007)

1.1.1 Apical Constriction in the lateral line Primordium

Previous studies suggested that in the lateral line primordium apical constriction is induced by Fgf signaling.

1.1.2 Image data

1.2 Measurements

Since apical constriction is a 3D morphological feature, it has to be measured on 3D segmented cells. In general, a number of assumptions can be made about apical constriction…

  • The apical side in a cluster of constricting cells is constricted
  • Apical constriction is independent of orientation
    • Cells can be horizonzally constricted
    • Cells can also be vertically constricted
  • Apical constriction is independent of height
  • Apical constriction is independent of volume / size of a cell

1.2.1 Apical Constriction Index

1.2.2 Trigonometry

Looking at a constricted 3D cell from any perspective in XZ, it roughly depicts a 2D triangle. If the length of at least two sites of this triangle are known, the apical angle (phi) can be deduced from that. Phi would be, theoretically, a direct readout for how much a cell is constricted.

If one angle of a triangle is 90 degrees and one of the other angles is known, the third is thereby fixed, because the three angles of any triangle add up to 180 degrees. The two acute angles therefore add up to 90 degrees: they are complementary angles. The shape of a triangle is completely determined, except for similarity, by the angles. Once the angles are known, the ratios of the sides are determined, regardless of the overall size of the triangle. If the length of one of the sides is known, the other two are determined. These ratios are given by the following trigonometric functions of the known angle A, where a, b and c refer to the lengths of the sides in the accompanying figure: - wiki

library(plyr)
library(dplyr)
read.data.all.3D <- function(file){
    dat <- read.table(file, sep="\t", header=TRUE)
    dat$Nb <- NULL
    dat$Obj <- file
    dat$X <- NULL
    Zcal <- dat$CZ..unit./dat$CZ..pix.                # To transform pix to unit value in Z
    XYcal <- dat$CX..unit./dat$CX..pix.               # To transform pix to unit value in X and Y
    dat$Height <- (dat$Zmax..pix.-dat$Zmin..pix.)*Zcal  # calculate Height and transform to unit value
    dat$Height <- dat$Height*Zcal                       # calculate Height and transform to unit value
    dat$Length <- (dat$Xmax..pix.-dat$Xmin..pix.)*XYcal # calculate Length and transform to unit value
    dat$Width <- (dat$Ymax..pix.-dat$Ymin..pix.)*XYcal  # calculate Width and transform to unit value
    dat$HF <- dat$Height/dat$Feret..unit.               # calculate Height/Feret ratio
    # calculate Phi
    dat$Phi <- ((atan(dat$Height/dat$Feret..unit.))*180)/pi
    adj <- dat$Length/2
    opp <- dat$Height
    hyp <- dat$Feret..unit.
    dat$Phi <- ((atan(adj/opp))*180)/pi
    #dat$Phi <- ((asin(1/hyp))*180)/pi
    #dat$ACPhi <- 180-((((atan(dat$Height/dat$Feret..unit.))*180)/pi)+90) # <- ACPhi3
    dat$ACPhi <- 180-((((atan(adj/opp))*180)/pi)+90)  #                     <- ACPhi2
    #dat$ACPhi <- asin(dat$Height/dat$Feret..unit.)    #                    <- ACPhi1
    trail <- ((max(dat$CX..pix.)-min(dat$CX..pix.))*XYcal[1])*0.25
    dat$CXN <- (max(dat$CX..pix.)-dat$CX..pix.)*XYcal   # normalize CX against leading edge
    #dat <- subset(dat, dat$CXN < quantile(dat$CXN, 0.99, na.rm=TRUE) & dat$CXN > quantile(dat$CXN, 0.01, na.rm=TRUE))
    #lower <- subset(dat, dat$CXN > quantile(dat$CXN, 0.99, na.rm=TRUE))
    #print(lower$Label)
    #upper <- subset(dat, dat$CXN < quantile(dat$CXN, 0.01, na.rm=TRUE))
    #print(upper$Label)
    #trail <- quantile(dat$CXN, 0.2, na.rm=TRUE)
    print(trail)
    dat$FLsplit <- cut(dat$CXN, breaks = c(-Inf, trail, Inf), labels = c("leading", "trailing"))
    dat$SAV <- dat$Surf..unit./dat$Vol..unit.           # calculate Surface Area to Volume ratio 
    dat$VolN <- (1/min(dat$Vol..unit., na.rm=TRUE))*dat$Vol..unit.  # normalize Volumes
    dat$GT <- GT                                        # add Genotype
    dat$CZ..pix. <- NULL
    dat$CX..pix. <- NULL
    dat$CY..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Xmin..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Xmax..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Ymin..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Ymax..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Zmin..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Zmax..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Vol..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Surf..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Spher..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Comp..pix. <- NULL
    return(dat)
  }
read.data.all.ACI <- function(file){
    dat <- read.table(file, header=TRUE)
    dat$objlabelArray <- NULL
    dat$ACI <- dat$basalArray/dat$apicalArray
    return(dat)
  }
